      "flip_evidence_text": "in the event any Representative of any Acquired Corporation takes any action (or omits to take any action) which, if taken or not taken by the Acquired Corporation, would constitute a breach of this Section 4.3 ... knowingly facilitate, induce, assist or encourage (including by way of furnishing non-public information)",
      "notes": "The deemed-breach mechanism is correct, but Section 4.3(b) imposes knowledge requirements (e.g., “knowingly facilitate”) for many prohibited acts. Because the deemed breach in clause (f) applies only to Representative actions that “would constitute a breach” of Section 4.3, the underlying intent/knowledge elements must still be satisfied; it is therefore not accurate to say liability is triggered “regardless of intent or knowledge.”"
    }
  ]
}

